{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775861850448,"sessionID":"ses_286630481ffeOc2rtsZEj0QW9M","part":{"id":"prt_d799d592b001HfdQP8sKiZc9N9","messageID":"msg_d799d4148001NaCUGk89ev5U7U","sessionID":"ses_286630481ffeOc2rtsZEj0QW9M","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-20e3374197bd45b48032bf57216db40b","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/changes/AR-016/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/changes/AR-016/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-016 — PicoD 文件管理 API Proposal\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: Extend PicoD's file management capabilities beyond the basic upload, list, and download operations implemented in AR-015. This adds comprehensive file system manipulation APIs including file deletion, directory creation, file copy/move, permissions modification, and archive operations (tar/zip) for AI agent workspace management.\n6: \n7: **Current State**: PicoD (AR-015) provides basic file operations: `POST /api/files` (upload), `GET /api/files?path=...` (list), `GET /api/files/*path` (download). Missing: deletion, directory creation, copy/move, permissions change, and archive handling.\n8: \n9: **Target State**: Full-featured file management API suite:\n10: - `DELETE /api/files/*path` — Delete files and directories\n11: - `POST /api/files/directory` — Create directories with optional mode\n12: - `POST /api/files/copy` — Copy files/directories within workspace\n13: - `POST /api/files/move` — Move/rename files/directories\n14: - `PATCH /api/files/*path` — Modify file permissions\n15: - `POST /api/files/archive` — Create tar/zip archives\n16: - `POST /api/files/extract` — Extract tar/zip archives\n17: \n18: ## Scope\n19: \n20: ### In Scope\n21: \n22: | Deliverable | Description |\n23: |-------------|-------------|\n24: | `pkg/picod/files.go` (extend) | Add DeleteFileHandler, CreateDirectoryHandler, CopyFileHandler, MoveFileHandler, ModifyPermissionsHandler |\n25: | `pkg/picod/archive.go` | New file: ArchiveHandler, ExtractHandler with tar/zip support |\n26: | `pkg/picod/files.go` structs | DeleteRequest, CreateDirectoryRequest, CopyRequest, MoveRequest, ModifyPermissionsRequest, ArchiveRequest, ExtractRequest |\n27: | `pkg/picod/server.go` (extend) | Register new file management routes |\n28: | `pkg/picod/picod_test.go` (extend) | Unit tests for all new handlers |\n29: \n30: ### Implementation Details\n31: \n32: #### Request/Response Structures\n33: \n34: **Delete**:\n35: ```go\n36: type DeleteRequest struct {\n37:     Path      string `json:\"path\" binding:\"required\"`\n38:     Recursive bool   `json:\"recursive\"` // For directory deletion\n39: }\n40: \n41: type DeleteResponse struct {\n42:     Path   string `json:\"path\"`\n43:     Deleted bool  `json:\"deleted\"`\n44: }\n45: ```\n46: \n47: **Create Directory**:\n48: ```go\n49: type CreateDirectoryRequest struct {\n50:     Path string `json:\"path\" binding:\"required\"`\n51:     Mode string `json:\"mode\"` // Octal, default 0755\n52: }\n53: \n54: type CreateDirectoryResponse struct {\n55:     Path     string    `json:\"path\"`\n56:     Mode     string    `json:\"mode\"`\n57:     Created  bool      `json:\"created\"`\n58: }\n59: ```\n60: \n61: **Copy**:\n62: ```go\n63: type CopyRequest struct {\n64:     Source string `json:\"source\" binding:\"required\"`\n65:     Dest   string `json:\"dest\" binding:\"required\"`\n66: }\n67: \n68: type CopyResponse struct {\n69:     Source string `json:\"source\"`\n70:     Dest   string `json:\"dest\"`\n71:     Copied bool   `json:\"copied\"`\n72: }\n73: ```\n74: \n75: **Move**:\n76: ```go\n77: type MoveRequest struct {\n78:     Source string `json:\"source\" binding:\"required\"`\n79:     Dest   string `json:\"dest\" binding:\"required\"`\n80: }\n81: \n82: type MoveResponse struct {\n83:     Source string `json:\"source\"`\n84:     Dest   string `json:\"dest\"`\n85:     Moved  bool   `json:\"moved\"`\n86: }\n87: ```\n88: \n89: **Modify Permissions**:\n90: ```go\n91: type ModifyPermissionsRequest struct {\n92:     Path string `json:\"path\" binding:\"required\"`\n93:     Mode string `json:\"mode\" binding:\"required\"` // Octal\n94: }\n95: \n96: type ModifyPermissionsResponse struct {\n97:     Path     string    `json:\"path\"`\n98:     OldMode  string    `json:\"old_mode\"`\n99:     NewMode  string    `json:\"new_mode\"`\n100: }\n101: ```\n102: \n103: **Archive**:\n104: ```go\n105: type ArchiveRequest struct {\n106:     SourcePath string `json:\"source_path\" binding:\"required\"` // Directory or file to archive\n107:     DestPath   string `json:\"dest_path\" binding:\"required\"`   // Output archive path\n108:     Format     string `json:\"format\"`                         // \"tar\" or \"zip\", default \"tar\"\n109: }\n110: \n111: type ArchiveResponse struct {\n112:     SourcePath string `json:\"source_path\"`\n113:     DestPath   string `json:\"dest_path\"`\n114:     Format     string `json:\"format\"`\n115:     Size       int64  `json:\"size\"`\n116: }\n117: ```\n118: \n119: **Extract**:\n120: ```go\n121: type ExtractRequest struct {\n122:     SourcePath string `json:\"source_path\" binding:\"required\"` // Archive to extract\n123:     DestPath   string `json:\"dest_path\"`                      // Destination directory, defaults to archive parent\n124: }\n125: \n126: type ExtractResponse struct {\n127:     SourcePath string     `json:\"source_path\"`\n128:     DestPath   string     `json:\"dest_path\"`\n129:     Files      []FileEntry `json:\"files\"` // Extracted files list\n130: }\n131: ```\n132: \n133: #### Route Registration Extension\n134: \n135: ```go\n136: api.DELETE(\"/files/*path\", s.DeleteFileHandler)\n137: api.POST(\"/files/directory\", s.CreateDirectoryHandler)\n138: api.POST(\"/files/copy\", s.CopyFileHandler)\n139: api.POST(\"/files/move\", s.MoveFileHandler)\n140: api.PATCH(\"/files/*path\", s.ModifyPermissionsHandler)\n141: api.POST(\"/files/archive\", s.ArchiveHandler)\n142: api.POST(\"/files/extract\", s.ExtractHandler)\n143: ```\n144: \n145: #### Handler Implementations\n146: \n147: | Handler | Logic |\n148: |---------|-------|\n149: | `DeleteFileHandler` | Wildcard path; `os.Stat` to check if file or dir; file: `os.Remove`; dir: `os.RemoveAll` if recursive, else error if non-empty |\n150: | `CreateDirectoryHandler` | JSON bind; sanitize; `parseFileMode`; `os.MkdirAll`; return created status |\n151: | `CopyFileHandler` | Sanitize source/dest; `os.Stat` source; file: `io.Copy`; dir: recursive copy via `filepath.Walk` |\n152: | `MoveFileHandler` | Sanitize source/dest; `os.Rename`; handles cross-directory moves |\n153: | `ModifyPermissionsHandler` | Wildcard path; `os.Chmod` with parsed mode; return old/new mode |\n154: | `ArchiveHandler` | Sanitize paths; `archive/tar` or `archive/zip`; walk source, add entries; write to dest |\n155: | `ExtractHandler` | Sanitize paths; detect format by extension or request field; `tar.NewReader` or `zip.OpenReader`; extract each entry |\n156: \n157: #### Constants\n158: \n159: | Name | Value | Purpose |\n160: |------|-------|---------|\n161: | `defaultDirMode` | `0755` | Default directory creation mode |\n162: | `maxArchiveSize` | `100 << 20` (100 MiB) | Maximum archive size for extraction safety |\n163: | `allowedArchiveFormats` | `[\"tar\", \"zip\", \"tar.gz\", \"tgz\"]` | Supported archive formats |\n164: \n165: ### Out of Scope\n166: \n167: - Symlink creation/resolution API (separate security concerns)\n168: - Multiple workspace roots\n169: - File content search/grep API\n170: - File locking/concurrent access control\n171: - Chunked/streaming large file operations\n172: - Remote file URLs (no external fetch)\n173: - File checksum verification (MD5/SHA)\n174: - Quarantine/sandbox escape detection beyond existing sanitizePath\n175: - Recursive permission modification\n176: - File ownership change (chown)\n177: \n178: ## Impact Analysis\n179: \n180: ### Upstream Dependencies\n181: \n182: | Dependency | Version | Impact |\n183: |------------|---------|--------|\n184: | `github.com/gin-gonic/gin` | v1.10+ | HTTP framework; existing from AR-015 |\n185: | `archive/tar` | Standard | Tar archive creation/extraction |\n186: | `archive/zip` | Standard | Zip archive creation/extraction |\n187: | `compress/gzip` | Standard | Gzip compression for tar.gz |\n188: | `io` | Standard | Stream copying for file operations |\n189: | `filepath` | Standard | Path walking for recursive operations |\n190: | `os` | Standard | File system operations |\n191: \n192: ### Downstream Consumers\n193: \n194: | Consumer | Method Usage |\n195: |----------|--------------|\n196: | CodeInterpreter Sandbox Pods | Directory creation for output folders; archive extraction for uploaded packages; cleanup via delete |\n197: | Agent Runtime Sandbox Pods | Move/rename for artifact organization; copy for backup; permissions for security staging |\n198: | Python SDK | Full file manipulation API calls; archive handling for dataset uploads |\n199: | Router | No direct impact; JWT auth unchanged |\n200: \n201: ### Breaking Change Considerations\n202: \n203: - **New Routes Only**: All additions are new routes; no existing endpoints modified\n204: - **Backward Compatible**: AR-015 file APIs remain unchanged\n205: - **Behavioral Consistency**: Same sanitizePath security applied to all new operations\n206: - **Archive Format**: Only tar/zip supported; other formats rejected with error\n207: \n208: ### Compatibility Notes\n209: \n210: 1. **Path Security**: All new operations use existing `sanitizePath` for workspace jail enforcement\n211: 2. **Recursive Operations**: Delete/copy with recursive flag; explicit flag prevents accidental mass deletion\n212: 3. **Archive Paths**: Archive extraction validates each entry path against workspace jail\n213: 4. **Move Semantics**: `os.Rename` may fail across filesystem boundaries; error returned if unsupported\n214: 5. **Permissions Octal**: Same `parseFileMode` pattern as upload; octal string input\n215: \n216: ## Alternatives Considered\n217: \n218: ### Alternative 1: Single Multi-Operation Endpoint\n219: \n220: **Approach**: `POST /api/files/operation` with `operation` field specifying copy/move/delete/etc.\n221: \n222: | Aspect | Evaluation |\n223: |--------|------------|\n224: | Pros | Single endpoint; consistent request structure |\n225: | Cons | Less RESTful; harder to document; mixed error handling |\n226: \n227: **Decision**: Rejected. Separate endpoints follow REST conventions, enable granular error handling, and match existing PicoD API style.\n228: \n229: ### Alternative 2: External Archive Tools\n230: \n231: **Approach**: Use `tar`/`zip` CLI commands via `exec.CommandContext` for archive operations.\n232: \n233: | Aspect | Evaluation |\n234: |--------|------------|\n235: | Pros | Leverages well-tested tools; supports all formats |\n236: | Cons | Depends on container having tools installed; security via command execution; less portable |\n237: \n238: **Decision**: Rejected. Native Go `archive/tar` and `archive/zip` libraries are cross-platform, don't require container dependencies, and integrate with existing sanitization logic.\n239: \n240: ### Alternative 3: File Operations via Command Execution\n241: \n242: **Approach**: Users implement file operations via `POST /api/execute` with shell commands (`rm`, `mkdir`, `cp`, `mv`).\n243: \n244: | Aspect | Evaluation |\n245: |--------|------------|\n246: | Pros | No new code; maximum flexibility |\n247: | Cons | Shell-dependent; less secure; no structured error responses; harder to audit |\n248: \n249: **Decision**: Rejected. Dedicated API endpoints provide structured responses, consistent path security, and audit-friendly operation logs.\n250: \n251: ### Alternative 4: WebDAV Protocol\n252: \n253: **Approach**: Expose WebDAV server for file operations (PROPFIND, COPY, MOVE, DELETE).\n254: \n255: | Aspect | Evaluation |\n256: |--------|------------|\n257: | Pros | Standard protocol; existing client libraries; directory listing built-in |\n258: | Cons | Different auth integration; more complex middleware; not JSON-based |\n259: \n260: **Decision**: Rejected. REST/JSON API matches PicoD's existing design and Router integration. WebDAV would require separate auth handling and different middleware stack.\n261: \n262: ### Alternative 5: Batch Operations Endpoint\n263: \n264: **Approach**: `POST /api/files/batch` accepting array of operations in single request.\n265: \n266: | Aspect | Evaluation |\n267: |--------|------------|\n268: | Pros | Reduced round trips; atomic grouping |\n269: | Cons | Complex error handling; partial failure semantics unclear |\n270: \n271: **Decision**: Deferred. Batch operations are valuable but add complexity. Initial implementation uses single-operation endpoints; batch can be added later without breaking changes.\n272: \n273: ## Risks\n274: \n275: | Risk | Mitigation |\n276: |------|------------|\n277: | Recursive delete destroys workspace | `Recursive` flag required for directory deletion; non-empty dir without flag returns error |\n278: | Archive extraction path escape | Validate each archive entry path via `sanitizePath`; reject entries attempting `..` escape |\n279: | Large archive DoS | `maxArchiveSize` = 100 MiB; reject archives exceeding limit; streaming extraction avoids memory exhaustion |\n280: | Copy infinite loop (circular symlink) | `sanitizePath` resolves symlinks; skip symlinks in recursive copy or resolve target first |\n281: | Move across filesystem boundaries | `os.Rename` returns specific error; handler detects and returns appropriate message |\n282: | Concurrent modification conflict | No locking; operations are atomic at OS level; last-write-wins semantics |\n283: | Permission change security | Mode limited to `<= 0777`; same `parseFileMode` validation as upload |\n284: | Archive format confusion | Detect format by file extension + request field; reject unsupported formats |\n285: \n286: ## Implementation Checklist\n287: \n288: 1. **Delete Handler**\n289:    - Wildcard path extraction\n290:    - `os.Stat` to determine type\n291:    - File: `os.Remove`\n292:    - Directory: check `recursive` flag; `os.RemoveAll` or error if non-empty\n293: \n294: 2. **Create Directory Handler**\n295:    - JSON bind `CreateDirectoryRequest`\n296:    - Sanitize path; `parseFileMode` (default 0755)\n297:    - `os.MkdirAll` for nested creation\n298:    - Return `CreateDirectoryResponse`\n299: \n300: 3. **Copy Handler**\n301:    - Sanitize source and dest\n302:    - `os.Stat` source; detect file vs dir\n303:    - File: `os.Open` + `io.Copy`\n304:    - Directory: `filepath.Walk` with recursive copy\n305: \n306: 4. **Move Handler**\n307:    - Sanitize source and dest\n308:    - `os.Rename`; handle cross-fs error\n309:    - Return `MoveResponse`\n310: \n311: 5. **Modify Permissions Handler**\n312:    - Wildcard path; JSON body for mode\n313:    - `os.Stat` to get old mode\n314:    - `parseFileMode` for new mode\n315:    - `os.Chmod`; return old/new modes\n316: \n317: 6. **Archive Handler** (new file)\n318:    - Sanitize source and dest paths\n319:    - Detect format from request/extension\n320:    - `tar.Create` or `zip.Create`\n321:    - Walk source; add entries with relative paths\n322:    - Close archive; return size\n323: \n324: 7. **Extract Handler** (new file)\n325:    - Sanitize source; resolve dest (default parent)\n326:    - Open archive; iterate entries\n327:    - For each entry: sanitize entry path; reject escapes\n328:    - Create directories; write files\n329:    - Return extracted file list\n330: \n331: 8. **Route Registration**\n332:    - Add DELETE, POST (directory/copy/move/archive/extract), PATCH routes\n333:    - All under `/api` with existing JWT auth middleware\n334: \n335: 9. **Tests**\n336:    - Delete: file, directory (recursive/non-recursive), non-empty without flag, nonexistent\n337:    - Create directory: single, nested, with mode, already exists\n338:    - Copy: file, directory, nonexistent source, dest exists\n339:    - Move: file, directory, cross-directory, nonexistent source\n340:    - Modify permissions: file, directory, invalid mode, nonexistent\n341:    - Archive: tar, zip, tar.gz, large source, nonexistent source\n342:    - Extract: tar, zip, tar.gz, path escape in archive, large archive rejection\n343: \n344: ## References\n345: \n346: - `code-execution/spec.md` — PicoD base requirements\n347: - `changes/AR-015/proposal.md` — Original PicoD implementation\n348: - `pkg/picod/files.go` — Existing file upload/list/download handlers\n349: - `pkg/picod/sanitize.go` — Path security logic\n350: - [Go archive/tar](https://pkg.go.dev/archive/tar)\n351: - [Go archive/zip](https://pkg.go.dev/archive/zip)\n\n(End of file - total 351 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-016 — PicoD 文件管理 API Proposal\n\n## Purpose\n\nExtend PicoD's file management capabilities beyond the basic upload, list, and download operations implemented in AR-015. This adds comprehensive file system manipulation APIs including file deletion, directory creation, file copy/move, permissions modification, and archive operations (tar/zip) for AI agent workspace management.\n\n**Current State**: PicoD (AR-015) provides basic file operations: `POST /api/files` (upload), `GET /api/files?path=...` (list), `GET /api/files/*path` (download). Missing: deletion, directory creation, copy/move, permissions change, and archive handling.\n\n**Target State**: Full-featured file management API suite:\n- `DELETE /api/files/*path` — Delete files and directories\n- `POST /api/files/directory` — Create directories with optional mode\n- `POST /api/files/copy` — Copy files/directories within workspace\n- `POST /api/files/move` — Move/rename files/directories\n- `PATCH /api/files/*path` — Modify file permissions\n- `POST /api/files/archive` — Create tar/zip archives\n- `POST /api/files/extract` — Extract tar/zip archives\n\n## Scope\n\n### In Scope","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/changes/AR-016/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775861850421,"end":1775861850445}}}}
